10 Scrolls at a Time

Mapping the Rhythm of My Scrolling Addiction

It starts like this -

I open TikTok for “just a minute”

One scroll….

becomes two…

then ten…

then suddenly I have time-travelled through hundreds of videos

But what actually makes me stop and watch?

What themes keep popping up?

When do certain feelings hit hardest?

In this visual data story, I use three plots (and far too much of my own TikTok data) to uncover the rhythm behind my daily doom-scrolling addiction

Just One More Video…

TikTok runs on fast dopamine - short, snappy, scroll-stopping content - but how short is short ?

Histogram of TikTok video durations, grouped by ad presence with a density curve overlay

This plot shows how long the videos on my For You Page really are and whether they come with a side of capitalism.

Quick beats are dominating

  • Most of the videos on my For You Page are short and snappy and usually under 60 seconds

  • Advertisements tend to appear more often in the 30 to 60 second range

  • The density curve shows a sharp rise and then a quick drop-off which reflects how TikTok encourages fast beat viewing

Wait… Why Is That Video Longer?

Just when I thought I have figured out the rhythm something shifts!

A box plot showing how video lengths vary across different content themes with overlapping dot-count sizes representing frequency

This plot breaks down video duration by general theme which shows how the content type controls the tempo

General themes bring tempo as not all content dances to the same beat

  • Education and News & Issues videos tend to be longer which allow for deeper dives and more explanation
  • Entertainment and Lifestyle videos prefer shorter video duration which is designed to delivery quick impact
  • The size of each dot shows how often a particular general theme and duration combo appeared. This reveals the video themes that maps my scrolling addiction

Ooh! Why Does That Hit Different on a Thursday?

Scroll….

Scroll….

What is this feeling…

so sudden….and new

A heat map showing weighted engagement scores for different video emotions across each day of the week. Darker tiles represent higher engagement

This heat map tracks the engagement by emotion and day of the week. I used a weighted score based on likes, comments, and shares

  • For You Page video content that express high energy emotions like happiness and excitement tend to receive more engagement in the middle of the week, especially on Wednesdays and Thursdays

  • Calmer and sadder video content quietly rise in engagement on Sundays

  • The video content’s emotional tone appears to influence how much viewers interact, we can see this from the likes, comments, and shares are not evenly spread

  • This heat map reveals how emotional themes pulse through the week which suggests that creators may be timing content to align with the shifting moods

  • The dashed line splits the week by weekend and weekday to highlight the shift in emotional engagement as the tempo of the week changes
